It's always super busy and so you're gonna have to wait a while for your food, and if you're on T-Mobile you won't get reception in much of the place. Doesn't matter though, because the food and service are about as good as it gets. The perfect hangover food.

This place is absolutely amazing. I had cheesy grits with a poached egg and pork belly on top, but I also had to try a little bit of what my fellow breakfast crew were having, so I also got to try the crawfish beignets, the biscuit, the pot pie, and some of the shrimp and goat cheese omelette. The food is incredibly rich, and heavy, but I was not able to stop eating when I was full because of how good everything was. In particular, I loved the texture, cut, and serving of the pork belly on the super thick, flavorful and cheesy grits. None of my food needed any more seasoning, but none of it was too overpowering. The paprika/chili based seasoning on top of the beignets was a little dusty, but I didn't inhale any or anything, so it was nicely executed in my opinion. The cajun spiced cheesy crawdad mix in the center was hot but not mouth scorching, and they were just amazing. The pot pie wasn't much of a pie per se, it seemed to me to be more of a bowl of cheesy goodness with some crusty bread thrown in in rather than a pie crust, but it was a nice interpretation of it, and it was delicious. The biscuit was a biscuit, nothing too extraordinary, but the strawberry preserves were great with it, and one of my personal faves for breakfast, so that was nice. The shrimp and goat cheese omelet was also amazing. it was probably the lightest of our breakfasts, but by no means small or insubstantial. This place was a real highlight in my quick turnaround trip to SF, and the next time I'm in town, I'm going to give it another go. Tough to do when there's so much selection, but this place warrants it.

Can't go back to SoCal without having a full Sunday brunch at Brenda's! The wait here is terrible (at least 1-2 hours), but we do it anyway every time we are in the area. We always order beignets even though they fill us up before our entrees arrive. There are three per order and we usually split them up. We've had all of them: the plain is good, and well, traditional. The chocolate has a large amount of Ghirardelli chocolate in it. The apple one tastes like a McDonald's apple pie. Crawfish is interesting and savory. If you can't decide which to get you can always sample them all withe the "Beignet Flight" (your choice of 4). ...Kinda weird, though, the last time we ordered 3 apples, but got 2 chocolates with 1 apple (surprise?!). A big favorite to get for the pork-lovers is the pork belly dish. They're almost always out of these when we are here though... Another favorite is the shrimp & grits (sautéed shrimp, cheddar grits, spicy tomato-bacon gravy). It's a bit heavy to have before a long drive, but there's something irresistible about the cheesy grits smothered with salty gravy... (mouth watering now). I made the mistake of wanting to try something new and ordered the grillades & grits (beef cutlets braised in spicy creole gravy, served with grits, 2 eggs any style, plus cream biscuit or toast). The cutlets were a bit dried out and chewy. The gravy sauce made the whole dish taste similar to Taco Bell taco meat. I had expected a beefy version of the shrimp & grits -- no dice. Of course, you can't go wrong with classic oldies, but goodies like the eggs benedict, french toast (it's a lotta toast for 1 person!), or the homemade granola pancakes with fruit (HUUUUGE!). Lastly, you must not leave without trying their sweet watermelon house tea (which just tastes like fresh watermelon juice). It's $2.75, but with unlimited refills! It's usually hustling and bustling here for Sunday Brunch; I've never seen it not busy. The food's spectacular. The service is hit-or-miss (usually the servers here are too busy to smile or give you time to complete your sentence before they hurry off again).

The crawfish beignets are amazing! This was my first time eating here, and my friend and I shared crawfish beignets and each ordered our own entrees. I ordered the hang town fry, and she got the cinnamon battered brioche French toast. The hang town fry was a crispy oyster, scallion, and bacon scramble with grits or hash and cream biscuit or toast. Both were delicious, especially the pecan syrup on the French toast, which made it taste buttery and warm. Out of the three dishes we ordered, the beignets stand out the most. They were stuffed with scallions and cheddar and topped with cayenne. The gooey cheddar and scallions reminded me of eating grilled cheese, and the texture of the beignets was perfectly crispy. The cayenne added a little bit of flair to the savory perfection. I will definitely be coming back and ordering more crawfish beignets.

Now I have never had beignets as good as at Cafe du Monde in New Orleans (and that's as it should be) - but the beignets here are creative and fun to share.

    Can't go back to SoCal without having a full Sunday brunch at Brenda's!

    The wait here is terrible (at least 1-2 hours), but we do it anyway every time we are in the area.

    We always order beignets even though they fill us up before our entrees arrive.  There are three per order and we usually split them up.  We've had all of them:  the plain is good, and well, traditional.  The chocolate has a large amount of Ghirardelli chocolate in it.  The apple one tastes like a McDonald's apple pie.  Crawfish is interesting and savory.  If you can't decide which to get you can always sample them all withe the "Beignet Flight" (your choice of 4).  ...Kinda weird, though, the last time we ordered 3 apples, but got 2 chocolates with 1 apple (surprise?!).

    A big favorite to get for the pork-lovers is the pork belly dish.  They're almost always out of these when we are here though...  

    Another favorite is the shrimp & grits (sautéed shrimp, cheddar grits, spicy tomato-bacon gravy).  It's a bit heavy to have before a long drive, but there's something irresistible about the cheesy grits smothered with salty gravy...  (mouth watering now).

    I made the mistake of wanting to try something new and ordered the grillades & grits (beef cutlets braised in spicy creole gravy, served with grits, 2 eggs any style, plus cream biscuit or toast).  The cutlets were a bit dried out and chewy.  The gravy sauce made the whole dish taste similar to Taco Bell taco meat.  I had expected a beefy version of the shrimp & grits -- no dice.

    Of course, you can't go wrong with classic oldies, but goodies like the eggs benedict, french toast (it's a lotta toast for 1 person!), or the homemade granola pancakes with fruit (HUUUUGE!).

    Lastly, you must not leave without trying their sweet watermelon house tea (which just tastes like fresh watermelon juice).  It's $2.75, but with unlimited refills!

    It's usually hustling and bustling here for Sunday Brunch; I've never seen it not busy.  The food's spectacular.  The service is hit-or-miss (usually the servers here are too busy to smile or give you time to complete your sentence before they hurry off again).

    4/18/2013Previous review

    Brenda's is as good as Louisiana style soul food gets in San Francisco.  The space has been creatively and cost effectively remodeled to accommodate a clientele that is often down the block clamoring for a table.  The service is efficient and the food is absolutely mouth watering.  The watermelon iced tea is delicious and the po' boys are very popular.  If you have dietary restrictions, just alert them and they will make something very special happen for you.  There are daily specials, but the Chicken Etoufee is delicious, they even make red beans and rice with sausage taste spectacular.  The only drawback is no reservations, you just drop by, put your name on the blackboard, and read the specials while you wait for a table to open up.  I have had great breakfast meetings here as well as lunches, once you are seated service is fast, food is hot and fantastic, and the waitstaff is attentive.
    Worth the wait!!!
    Also, depending upon what you order, the bill can be cheap or moderate, its entirely up to you.

    The crawfish beignets are amazing! This was my first time eating here, and my friend and I shared crawfish beignets and each ordered our own entrees. I ordered the hang town fry, and she got the cinnamon battered brioche French toast. The hang town fry was a crispy oyster, scallion, and bacon scramble with grits or hash and cream biscuit or toast. Both were delicious, especially the pecan syrup on the French toast, which made it taste buttery and warm. Out of the three dishes we ordered, the beignets stand out the most. They were stuffed with scallions and cheddar and topped with cayenne. The gooey cheddar and scallions reminded me of eating grilled cheese, and the texture of the beignets was perfectly crispy. The cayenne added a little bit of flair to the savory perfection. I will definitely be coming back and ordering more crawfish beignets.

    Had a wonderful brunch with 6 friends here.  Lots of shared dishes and lots of down home flavorful food in a nice atmosphere (high ceilings, modern southern decor).  There's a lot of calories in everything, but once in a while I don't mind.

    We had gingerbread pancakes (yummy!), pork belly and cheddar cheese with grits, and the beef grillades and grits (LOVE the cajun gravy and debris), beignet sampler.  

    Now I have never had beignets as good as at Cafe du Monde in New Orleans (and that's as it should be) - but the beignets here are creative and fun to share.
